# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chip-seq
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] ChIP-seq is primarily used to determine how transcription factors and other chromatin-associated proteins influence phenotype-affecting mechanisms.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Determining how proteins interact with DNA to regulate gene expression is essential for fully understanding many biological processes and disease states.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] This epigenetic information is complementary to genotype and expression analysis.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] ChIP-seq technology is currently seen primarily as an alternative to ChIP-chip which requires a hybridization array.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] This introduces some bias, as an array is restricted to a fixed number of probes.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Sequencing, by contrast, is thought to have less bias, although the sequencing bias of different sequencing technologies is not yet fully understood.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Specific DNA sites in direct physical interaction with transcription factors and other proteins can be isolated by chromatin immunoprecipitation.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] ChIP produces a library of target DNA sites bound to a protein of interest.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Massively parallel sequence analyses are used in conjunction with whole-genome sequence databases to analyze the interaction pattern of any protein with DNA, or the pattern of any epigenetic chromatin modifications.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] This can be applied to the set of ChIP-able proteins and modifications, such as transcription factors, polymerases and transcriptional machinery, structural proteins, protein modifications, and DNA modifications.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] As an alternative to the dependence on specific antibodies, different methods have been developed to find the superset of all nucleosome-depleted or nucleosome-disrupted active regulatory regions in the genome, like DNase-Seq and FAIRE-Seq.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] ChIP is a powerful method to selectively enrich for DNA sequences bound by a particular protein in living cells.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] However, the widespread use of this method has been limited by the lack of a sufficiently robust method to identify all of the enriched DNA sequences.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] The ChIP wet lab protocol contains ChIP and hybridization.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] There are essentially five parts to the ChIP protocol that aid in better understanding the overall process of ChIP.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] In order to carry out the ChIP, the first step is cross-linking using formaldehyde and large batches of the DNA in order to obtain a useful amount.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] The cross-links are made between the protein and DNA, but also between RNA and other proteins.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] The second step is the process of chromatin fragmentation which breaks up the chromatin in order to get high quality DNA pieces for ChIP analysis in the end.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] These fragments should be cut to become under 500 base pairs each to have the best outcome for genome mapping.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] The third step is called chromatin immunoprecipitation, which is what ChIP is short for.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] The ChIP process enhances specific crosslinked DNA-protein complexes using an antibody against the protein of interest followed by incubation and centrifugation to obtain the immunoprecipitation.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] The immunoprecipitation step also allows for the removal of non-specific binding sites.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] The fourth step is DNA recovery and purification, taking place by the reversed effect on the cross-link between DNA and protein to separate them and cleaning DNA with an extraction.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] The fifth and final step is the analyzation step of the ChIP protocol by the process of qPCR, ChIP-on-chip (hybrid array) or ChIP sequencing.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Oligonucleotide adaptors are then added to the small stretches of DNA that were bound to the protein of interest to enable massively parallel sequencing.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Through the analysis, the sequences can then be identified and interpreted by the gene or region to where the protein was bound.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] After size selection, all the resulting ChIP-DNA fragments are sequenced simultaneously using a genome sequencer.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] A single sequencing run can scan for genome-wide associations with high resolution, meaning that features can be located precisely on the chromosomes.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] ChIP-chip, by contrast, requires large sets of tiling arrays for lower resolution.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] There are many new sequencing methods used in this sequencing step.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Some technologies that analyze the sequences can use cluster amplification of adapter-ligated ChIP DNA fragments on a solid flow cell substrate to create clusters of approximately 1000 clonal copies each.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] The resulting high density array of template clusters on the flow cell surface is sequenced by a genome analyzing program.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Each template cluster undergoes sequencing-by-synthesis in parallel using novel fluorescently labelled reversible terminator nucleotides.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Templates are sequenced base-by-base during each read.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Then, the data collection and analysis software aligns sample sequences to a known genomic sequence to identify the ChIP-DNA fragments.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Sensitivity of this technology depends on the depth of the sequencing run (i.e. the number of mapped sequence tags), the size of the genome and the distribution of the target factor.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] The sequencing depth is directly correlated with cost.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] If abundant binders in large genomes have to be mapped with high sensitivity, costs are high as an enormously high number of sequence tags will be required.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] This is in contrast to ChIP-chip in which the costs are not correlated with sensitivity.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Unlike microarray-based ChIP methods, the precision of the ChIP-seq assay is not limited by the spacing of predetermined probes.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] By integrating a large number of short reads, highly precise binding site localization is obtained.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Compared to ChIP-chip, ChIP-seq data can be used to locate the binding site within few tens of base pairs of the actual protein binding site.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Tag densities at the binding sites are a good indicator of protein–DNA binding affinity, which makes it easier to quantify and compare binding affinities of a protein to different DNA sites.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] ChIP-seq offers an alternative to ChIP-chip.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] STAT1 experimental ChIP-seq data have a high degree of similarity to results obtained by ChIP-chip for the same type of experiment, with greater than 64% of peaks in shared genomic regions.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Because the data are sequence reads, ChIP-seq offers a rapid analysis pipeline as long as a high-quality genome sequence is available for read mapping and the genome doesn't have repetitive content that confuses the mapping process.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] ChIP-seq also has the potential to detect mutations in binding-site sequences, which may directly support any observed changes in protein binding and gene regulation.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] As with many high-throughput sequencing approaches, ChIP-seq generates extremely large data sets, for which appropriate computational analysis methods are required.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] To predict DNA-binding sites from ChIP-seq read count data, peak calling methods have been developed.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] One of the most popular methods is MACS which empirically models the shift size of ChIP-Seq tags, and uses it to improve the spatial resolution of predicted binding sites.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] MACS is optimized for higher resolution peaks, while another popular algorithm, SICER is programmed to call for broader peaks, spanning over kilobases to megabases in order to search for broader chromatin domains.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] SICER is more useful for histone marks spanning gene bodies.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] A mathematical more rigorous method BCP (Bayesian Change Point) can be used for both sharp and broad peaks with faster computational speed, see benchmark comparison of ChIP-seq peak-calling tools by Thomas *et al.* (2017).
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Another relevant computational problem is differential peak calling, which identifies significant differences in two ChIP-seq signals from distinct biological conditions.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Differential peak callers segment two ChIP-seq signals and identify differential peaks using Hidden Markov Models.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Examples for two-stage differential peak callers are ChIPDiff and ODIN.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] To reduce spurious sites from ChIP-seq, multiple experimental controls can be used to detect binding sites from an IP experiment.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] Bay2Ctrls adopts a Bayesian model to integrate the DNA input control for the IP, the mock IP and its corresponding DNA input control to predict binding sites from the IP.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] This approach is particularly effective for complex samples such as whole model organisms.
[src:chip-seq/chip-sequencing] In addition, the analysis indicates that for complex samples mock IP controls substantially outperform DNA input controls probably due to the active genomes of the samples.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The DNA-protein complexes (chromatin-protein) are then sheared into ~500 bp DNA fragments by sonication or nuclease digestion.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Cross-linked DNA fragments associated with the protein(s) of interest are selectively immunoprecipitated from the cell debris using an appropriate protein-specific antibody.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The associated DNA fragments are purified and their sequence is determined.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Enrichment of specific DNA sequences represents regions on the genome that the protein of interest is associated with *in vivo*.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] There are mainly two types of ChIP, primarily differing in the starting chromatin preparation.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The first uses reversibly cross-linked chromatin sheared by sonication called cross-linked ChIP (XChIP).
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Native ChIP (NChIP) uses native chromatin sheared by micrococcal nuclease digestion.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Cross-linked ChIP is mainly suited for mapping the DNA target of transcription factors or other chromatin-associated proteins, and uses reversibly cross-linked chromatin as starting material.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The agent for reversible cross-linking could be formaldehyde or UV light.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Then the cross-linked chromatin is usually sheared by sonication, providing fragments of 300–1000 base pairs (bp) in length.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Mild formaldehyde crosslinking followed by nuclease digestion has been used to shear the chromatin.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Chromatin fragments of 400–500 bp have proven to be suitable for ChIP assays as they cover two to three nucleosomes.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Cell debris in the sheared lysate is then cleared by sedimentation and protein–DNA complexes are selectively immunoprecipitated using specific antibodies to the protein(s) of interest.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The antibodies are commonly coupled to agarose, sepharose, or magnetic beads.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Alternatively, chromatin-antibody complexes can be selectively retained and eluted by inert polymer discs.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The immunoprecipitated complexes (i.e., the bead–antibody–protein–target DNA sequence complex) are then collected and washed to remove non-specifically bound chromatin, the protein–DNA cross-link is reversed and proteins are removed by digestion with proteinase K.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] An epitope-tagged version of the protein of interest, or *in vivo* biotinylation can be used instead of antibodies to the native protein of interest.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The DNA associated with the complex is then purified and identified by polymerase chain reaction (PCR), microarrays (ChIP-on-chip), molecular cloning and sequencing, or direct high-throughput sequencing (ChIP-Seq).
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Native ChIP is mainly suited for mapping the DNA target of histone modifiers.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Generally, native chromatin is used as starting chromatin.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] As histones wrap around DNA to form nucleosomes, they are naturally linked.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Then the chromatin is sheared by micrococcal nuclease digestion, which cuts DNA at the length of the linker, leaving nucleosomes intact and providing DNA fragments of one nucleosome (200 bp) to five nucleosomes (1000 bp) in length.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Thereafter, methods similar to XChIP are used for clearing the cell debris, immunoprecipitating the protein of interest, removing protein from the immunoprecipitated complex, and purifying and analyzing the complex-associated DNA.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The major advantage of NChIP is antibody specificity.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Most antibodies to modified histones are raised against unfixed, synthetic peptide antigens.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The epitopes they need to recognize in the XChIP may be disrupted or destroyed by formaldehyde cross-linking, particularly as the cross-links are likely to involve lysine e-amino groups in the N-terminals, disrupting the epitopes.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] This is likely to explain the consistently low efficiency of XChIP protocols compared to NChIP.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] But XChIP and NChIP have different aims and advantages relative to each other.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] XChIP is for mapping target sites of transcription factors and other chromatin-associated proteins; NChIP is for mapping target sites of histone modifiers (see Table 1).
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Chromatin Immunoprecipitation sequencing, also known as ChIP-seq, is an experimental technique used to identify transcription factor binding events throughout an entire genome.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Knowing how the proteins in the human body interact with DNA to regulate gene expression is a key component of our knowledge of human diseases and biological processes.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] ChIP-seq is the primary technique to complete this task, as it has proven to be extremely effective in resolving how proteins and transcription factors influence phenotypical mechanisms.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Overall ChIP-seq has risen to be a very efficient method for determining these factors, but there is a rivaling method known as ChIP-on-chip.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] ChIP-on-chip, also known as ChIP-chip, is an experimental technique used to isolate and identify genomic sites occupied by specific DNA-binding proteins in living cells.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] ChIP-on-chip is a relatively newer technique, as it was introduced in 2001 by Peggy Farnham and Michael Zhang.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] ChIP-on-chip gets its name by combining the methods of Chromatin Immunoprecipitation and DNA microarray, thus creating ChIP-on-chip.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The two methods seek similar results, as they both strive to find protein binding sites that can help identify elements in the human genome.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Those elements in the human genome are important for the advancement of knowledge in human diseases and biological processes.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The difference between ChIP-seq and ChIP-chip is established by the specific site of the protein binding identification.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The main difference comes from the efficacy of the two techniques, ChIP-seq produces results with higher sensitivity and spatial resolution because of the wide range of genomic coverage.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Even though ChIP-seq has proven to be more efficient than ChIP-chip, ChIP-seq is not always the first choice for scientists.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The cost and accessibility of ChIP-seq is a major disadvantage, which has led to the more predominant use of ChIP-chip in laboratories across the world.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Lis and David Gilmour, at the time a graduate student in the Lis lab, used UV irradiation, a zero-length protein-nucleic acid crosslinking agent, to covalently cross-link proteins bound to DNA in living bacterial cells.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Following lysis of cross-linked cells and immunoprecipitation of bacterial RNA polymerase, DNA associated with enriched RNA polymerase was hybridized to probes corresponding to different regions of known genes to determine the in vivo distribution and density of RNA polymerase at these genes.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] A year later they used the same methodology to study the distribution of eukaryotic RNA polymerase II on fruit fly heat shock genes.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] These reports are considered the pioneering studies in the field of chromatin immunoprecipitation.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] XChIP was further modified and developed by Alexander Varshavsky and co-workers, who examined the distribution of histone H4 on heat shock genes using formaldehyde cross-linking.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] This technique was extensively developed and refined thereafter.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] NChIP approach was first described by Hebbes *et al*., 1988, and has also been developed and refined quickly.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] The typical ChIP assay usually takes 4–5 days and requires 106~ 107 cells at least.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] Now new techniques on ChIP could be achieved as few as 100~1000 cells and completed within one day.
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] ChIP has also been applied for genome-wide analysis by combining with microarray technology (ChIP-on-chip) or second-generation DNA-sequencing technology (Chip-Sequencing).
[src:chip-seq/chromatin-immunoprecipitation] ChIP can also combine with paired-end tags sequencing in Chromatin Interaction Analysis using Paired End Tag sequencing (ChIA-PET), a technique developed for large-scale, de novo analysis of higher-order chromatin structures.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] DNA-binding proteins include transcription factors which modulate the process of transcription, various polymerases, nucleases which cleave DNA molecules, and histones which are involved in chromosome packaging and transcription in the cell nucleus.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] DNA-binding proteins can incorporate such domains as the zinc finger, the helix-turn-helix, and the leucine zipper (among many others) that facilitate binding to nucleic acid.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] There are also more unusual examples such as transcription activator like effectors.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Structural proteins that bind DNA are well-understood examples of non-specific DNA-protein interactions.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Within chromosomes, DNA is held in complexes with structural proteins.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] These proteins organize the DNA into a compact structure called chromatin.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] In eukaryotes, this structure involves DNA binding to a complex of small basic proteins called histones.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] In prokaryotes, multiple types of proteins are involved.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] The histones form a disk-shaped complex called a nucleosome, which contains two complete turns of double-stranded DNA wrapped around its surface.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] These non-specific interactions are formed through basic residues in the histones making ionic bonds to the acidic sugar-phosphate backbone of the DNA, and are therefore largely independent of the base sequence.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Chemical modifications of these basic amino acid residues include methylation, phosphorylation and acetylation.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] These chemical changes alter the strength of the interaction between the DNA and the histones, making the DNA more or less accessible to transcription factors and changing the rate of transcription.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Other non-specific DNA-binding proteins in chromatin include the high-mobility group (HMG) proteins, which bind to bent or distorted DNA.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Biophysical studies show that these architectural HMG proteins bind, bend and loop DNA to perform its biological functions.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] These proteins are important in bending arrays of nucleosomes and arranging them into the larger structures that form chromosomes.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Recently FK506 binding protein 25 (FBP25) was also shown to non-specifically bind to DNA which helps in DNA repair.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] A distinct group of DNA-binding proteins are the DNA-binding proteins that specifically bind single-stranded DNA.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] In humans, replication protein A is the best-understood member of this family and is used in processes where the double helix is separated, including DNA replication, recombination and DNA repair.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] These binding proteins seem to stabilize single-stranded DNA and protect it from forming stem-loops or being degraded by nucleases.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] In contrast, other proteins have evolved to bind to specific DNA sequences.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] The most intensively studied of these are the various transcription factors, which are proteins that regulate transcription.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Each transcription factor binds to one specific set of DNA sequences and activates or inhibits the transcription of genes that have these sequences near their promoters.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] The transcription factors do this in two ways.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Firstly, they can bind the RNA polymerase responsible for transcription, either directly or through other mediator proteins; this locates the polymerase at the promoter and allows it to begin transcription.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Alternatively, transcription factors can bind enzymes that modify the histones at the promoter.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] This alters the accessibility of the DNA template to the polymerase.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] These DNA targets can occur throughout an organism's genome.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Thus, changes in the activity of one type of transcription factor can affect thousands of genes.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Thus, these proteins are often the targets of the signal transduction processes that control responses to environmental changes or cellular differentiation and development.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] The specificity of these transcription factors' interactions with DNA come from the proteins making multiple contacts to the edges of the DNA bases, allowing them to *read* the DNA sequence.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Most of these base-interactions are made in the major groove, where the bases are most accessible.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Mathematical descriptions of protein-DNA binding taking into account sequence-specificity, and competitive and cooperative binding of proteins of different types are usually performed with the help of the lattice models.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Computational methods to identify the DNA binding sequence specificity have been proposed to make a good use of the abundant sequence data in the post-genomic era.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] In addition, progress has happened on structure-based prediction of binding specificity across protein families using deep learning.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Protein–DNA interactions occur when a protein binds a molecule of DNA, often to regulate the biological function of DNA, usually the expression of a gene.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Among the proteins that bind to DNA are transcription factors that activate or repress gene expression by binding to DNA motifs and histones that form part of the structure of DNA and bind to it less specifically.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Also proteins that repair DNA such as uracil-DNA glycosylase interact closely with it.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] In general, proteins bind to DNA in the major groove; however, there are exceptions.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Protein–DNA interactions are of mainly two types, either specific interaction, or non-specific interaction.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Recent single-molecule experiments showed that DNA binding proteins undergo rapid rebinding in order to bind in correct orientation for recognizing the target site.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Designing DNA-binding proteins that have a specified DNA-binding site has been an important goal for biotechnology.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Zinc finger proteins have been designed to bind to specific DNA sequences and this is the basis of zinc finger nucleases.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Recently transcription activator-like effector nucleases (TALENs) have been created which are based on natural proteins secreted by *Xanthomonas* bacteria via their type III secretion system when they infect various plant species.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] There are many *in vitro* and *in vivo* techniques which are useful in detecting DNA-Protein Interactions.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] The following lists some methods currently in use: Electrophoretic mobility shift assay (EMSA) is a widespread qualitative technique to study protein–DNA interactions of known DNA binding proteins.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] DNA-Protein-Interaction - Enzyme-Linked ImmunoSorbant Assay (DPI-ELISA) allows the qualitative and quantitative analysis of DNA-binding preferences of known proteins *in vitro*.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] This technique allows the analysis of protein complexes that bind to DNA (DPI-Recruitment-ELISA) or is suited for automated screening of several nucleotide probes due to its standard ELISA plate formate.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] DNase footprinting assay can be used to identify the specific sites of binding of a protein to DNA at basepair resolution.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Chromatin immunoprecipitation is used to identify the *in vivo* DNA target regions of a known transcription factor.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] This technique when combined with high throughput sequencing is known as ChIP-Seq and when combined with microarrays it is known as ChIP-chip.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Yeast one-hybrid System (Y1H) is used to identify which protein binds to a particular DNA fragment.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Bacterial one-hybrid system (B1H) is used to identify which protein binds to a particular DNA fragment.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Structure determination using X-ray crystallography has been used to give a highly detailed atomic view of protein–DNA interactions.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] Besides these methods, other techniques such as SELEX, PBM (protein binding microarrays), DNA microarray screens, DamID, FAIRE or more recently DAP-seq (DNA affinity purification sequencing) are used in the laboratory to investigate DNA-protein interaction *in vivo* and *in vitro*.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] The protein–DNA interactions can be modulated using stimuli like ionic strength of the buffer, macromolecular crowding, temperature, pH and electric field.
[src:chip-seq/dna-binding-protein] This can lead to reversible dissociation/association of the protein–DNA complex.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] In genetics, an **enhancer** is a short (50–1500 bp) region of DNA that can be bound by proteins (activators) to increase the likelihood that transcription of a particular gene will occur.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] These proteins are usually referred to as transcription factors.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] They can be located up to 1 Mbp (1,000,000 bp) away from the gene, upstream or downstream from the start site.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] There are hundreds of thousands of enhancers in the human genome.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] They are found in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Active enhancers typically get transcribed as enhancer or regulatory non-coding RNA, whose expression levels correlate with mRNA levels of target genes.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The first discovery of a eukaryotic enhancer was in the immunoglobulin heavy chain gene in 1983.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] This enhancer, located in the large intron, provided an explanation for the transcriptional activation of rearranged Vh gene promoters while unrearranged Vh promoters remained inactive.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Lately, enhancers have been shown to be involved in certain medical conditions, for example, myelosuppression.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Since 2022, scientists have used artificial intelligence to design synthetic enhancers and applied them in animal systems, first in a cell line, and one year later also in vivo.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] In eukaryotic cells the structure of the chromatin complex of DNA is folded in a way that functionally mimics the supercoiled state characteristic of prokaryotic DNA, so although the enhancer DNA may be far from the gene in a linear way, it is spatially close to the promoter and gene.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] This allows it to interact with the general transcription factors and RNA polymerase II.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The same mechanism holds true for silencers in the eukaryotic genome.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Silencers are antagonists of enhancers that, when bound to its proper transcription factors called repressors, repress the transcription of the gene.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Silencers and enhancers may be in close proximity to each other or may even be in the same region only differentiated by the transcription factor the region binds to.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] An enhancer may be located upstream or downstream of the gene it regulates.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Furthermore, an enhancer does not need to be located near the transcription initiation site to affect transcription, as some have been found located several hundred thousand base pairs upstream or downstream of the start site.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers do not act on the promoter region itself, but are bound by activator proteins as first shown by in vivo competition experiments.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Subsequently, molecular studies showed direct interactions with transcription factors and cofactors, including the mediator complex, which recruits polymerase II and the general transcription factors which then begin transcribing the genes.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers can also be found within introns.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] An enhancer's orientation may even be reversed without affecting its function; additionally, an enhancer may be excised and inserted elsewhere in the chromosome, and still affect gene transcription.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] That is one reason that introns polymorphisms may have effects although they are not translated.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers can also be found at the exonic region of an unrelated gene and they may act on genes on another chromosome.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers are bound by p300-CBP and their location can be predicted by ChIP-seq against this family of coactivators.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Gene expression in mammals is regulated by many cis-regulatory elements, including core promoters and promoter-proximal elements that are located near the transcription start sites of genes.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Core promoters are sufficient to direct transcription initiation, but generally have low basal activity.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Other important cis-regulatory modules are localized in DNA regions that are distant from the transcription start sites.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] These include enhancers, silencers, insulators and tethering elements.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Among this constellation of elements, enhancers and their associated transcription factors have a leading role in the regulation of gene expression.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] An enhancer localized in a DNA region distant from the promoter of a gene can have a very large effect on gene expression, with some genes undergoing up to 100-fold increased expression due to an activated enhancer.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers are regions of the genome that are major gene-regulatory elements.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers control cell-type-specific gene expression programs, most often by looping through long distances to come in physical proximity with the promoters of their target genes.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] While there are hundreds of thousands of enhancer DNA regions, for a particular type of tissue only specific enhancers are brought into proximity with the promoters that they regulate.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] In a study of brain cortical neurons, 24,937 loops were found, bringing enhancers to their target promoters.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Multiple enhancers, each often at tens or hundreds of thousands of nucleotides distant from their target genes, loop to their target gene promoters and can coordinate with each other to control the expression of their common target gene.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The schematic illustration in this section shows an enhancer looping around to come into close physical proximity with the promoter of a target gene.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The loop is stabilized by a dimer of a connector protein (e.g. dimer of CTCF or YY1), with one member of the dimer anchored to its binding motif on the enhancer and the other member anchored to its binding motif on the promoter (represented by the red zigzags in the illustration).
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Mediator (a complex usually consisting of about 26 proteins in an interacting structure) communicates regulatory signals from enhancer DNA-bound transcription factors directly to the RNA polymerase II (pol II) enzyme bound to the promoter.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers, when active, are generally transcribed from both strands of DNA with RNA polymerases acting in two different directions, producing two Enhancer RNAs (eRNAs) as illustrated in the Figure.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Like mRNAs, these eRNAs are usually protected by their 5′ cap.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] An inactive enhancer may be bound by an inactive transcription factor.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Phosphorylation of the transcription factor may activate it and that activated transcription factor may then activate the enhancer to which it is bound (see small red star representing phosphorylation of transcription factor bound to enhancer in the illustration).
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] An activated enhancer begins transcription of its RNA before activating transcription of messenger RNA from its target gene.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] There are numerous methods to study enhancers, such as site-directed mutagenesis, comparative genomics, or in-vitro analysis of transcription-factor binding assays (e.g.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] More recently, high-throughput methods have been established that allow scientists to analyze thousands of enhancers in parallel.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] For instance, massively parallel reporter assays (MPRAs) and self-transcribing active regulatory region sequencing (STARR-seq) have revolutionized enhancer characterization.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] However, MPRA and STARR-seq datasets generated in cell lines such as K562 found substantial inconsistencies in enhancer calls from different labs that are primarily due to technical variations in both experimental details and data processing.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] HACNS1 (also known as CENTG2 and located in the Human Accelerated Region 2) is a gene enhancer "that may have contributed to the evolution of the uniquely opposable human thumb, and possibly also modifications in the ankle or foot that allow humans to walk on two legs".
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Evidence to date shows that of the 110,000 gene enhancer sequences identified in the human genome, HACNS1 has undergone the most change during the evolution of humans following the split with the ancestors of chimpanzees.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] An enhancer near the gene GADD45g has been described that may regulate brain growth in chimpanzees and other mammals, but not in humans.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The GADD45G regulator in mice and chimps is active in regions of the brain where cells that form the cortex, ventral forebrain, and thalamus are located and may suppress further neurogenesis.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Loss of the GADD45G enhancer in humans may contribute to an increase of certain neuronal populations and to forebrain expansion in humans.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The development, differentiation and growth of cells and tissues require precisely regulated patterns of gene expression.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers work as cis-regulatory elements to mediate both spatial and temporal control of development by turning on transcription in specific cells and/or repressing it in other cells.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Thus, the particular combination of transcription factors and other DNA-binding proteins in a developing tissue controls which genes will be expressed in that tissue.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Enhancers allow the same gene to be used in diverse processes in space and time.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Traditionally, enhancers were identified by enhancer trap techniques using a reporter gene or by comparative sequence analysis and computational genomics.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] In genetically tractable models such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster,* for example, a reporter construct such as the *lacZ* gene can be randomly integrated into the genome using a P element transposon.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] If the reporter gene integrates near an enhancer, its expression will reflect the expression pattern driven by that enhancer.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Thus, staining the flies for LacZ expression or activity and cloning the sequence surrounding the integration site allows the identification of the enhancer sequence.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The development of genomic and epigenomic technologies, however, has dramatically changed the outlook for cis-regulatory modules (CRM) discovery.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] An example of NGS-based approach called DNase-seq have enabled identification of nucleosome-depleted, or open chromatin regions, which can contain CRM.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] More recently techniques such as ATAC-seq have been developed which require less starting material.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Nucelosome depleted regions can be identified in vivo through expression of Dam methylase, allowing for greater control of cell-type specific enhancer identification.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Computational methods include comparative genomics, clustering of known or predicted TF-binding sites, and supervised machine-learning approaches trained on known CRMs.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] All of these methods have proven effective for CRM discovery, but each has its own considerations and limitations, and each is subject to a greater or lesser number of false-positive identifications.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] In the comparative genomics approach, sequence conservation of non-coding regions can be indicative of enhancers.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Sequences from multiple species are aligned, and conserved regions are identified computationally.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Although much evidence has pointed to sequence conservation for critical developmental enhancers, other work has shown that the function of enhancers can be conserved with little or no primary sequence conservation.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] For example, the *RET* enhancers in humans have very little sequence conservation to those in zebrafish, yet both species' sequences produce nearly identical patterns of reporter gene expression in zebrafish.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The enhancers determining early segmentation in *Drosophila melanogaster* embryos are among the best characterized developmental enhancers.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] In the early fly embryo, the gap gene transcription factors are responsible for activating and repressing a number of segmentation genes, such as the pair rule genes.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The gap genes are expressed in blocks along the anterior-posterior axis of the fly along with other maternal effect transcription factors, thus creating zones within which different combinations of transcription factors are expressed.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The pair-rule genes are separated from one another by non-expressing cells.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Moreover, the stripes of expression for different pair-rule genes are offset by a few cell diameters from one another.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Thus, unique combinations of pair-rule gene expression create spatial domains along the anterior-posterior axis to set up each of the 14 individual segments.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The 480 bp enhancer responsible for driving the sharp stripe two of the pair-rule gene *even-skipped* (*eve*) has been well-characterized.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The enhancer contains 12 different binding sites for maternal and gap gene transcription factors.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Activating and repressing sites overlap in sequence.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] *Eve* is only expressed in a narrow stripe of cells that contain high concentrations of the activators and low concentration of the repressors for this enhancer sequence.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Other enhancer regions drive *eve* expression in 6 other stripes in the embryo.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Establishing body axes is a critical step in animal development.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] During mouse embryonic development, Nodal, a transforming growth factor-beta superfamily ligand, is a key gene involved in patterning both the anterior-posterior axis and the left-right axis of the early embryo.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The *Nodal* gene contains two enhancers: the Proximal Epiblast Enhancer (PEE) and the Asymmetric Enhancer (ASE).
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The PEE is upstream of the Nodal gene and drives *Nodal* expression in the portion of the primitive streak that will differentiate into the node (also referred to as the primitive node).
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The PEE turns on Nodal expression in response to a combination of Wnt signaling plus a second, unknown signal; thus, a member of the LEF/TCF transcription factor family likely binds to a TCF binding site in the cells in the node.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Diffusion of Nodal away from the node forms a gradient which then patterns the extending anterior-posterior axis of the embryo.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The ASE is an intronic enhancer bound by the fork head domain transcription factor Fox1.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Early in development, Fox1-driven Nodal expression establishes the visceral endoderm.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Later in development, Fox1 binding to the ASE drives *Nodal* expression on the left side of the lateral plate mesoderm, thus establishing left-right asymmetry necessary for asymmetric organ development in the mesoderm.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Establishing three germ layers during gastrulation is another critical step in animal development.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Each of the three germ layers has unique patterns of gene expression that promote their differentiation and development.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The endoderm is specified early in development by *Gata4* expression, and Gata4 goes on to direct gut morphogenesis later.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] *Gata4* expression is controlled in the early embryo by an intronic enhancer that binds another forkhead domain transcription factor, FoxA2.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Initially the enhancer drives broad gene expression throughout the embryo, but the expression quickly becomes restricted to the endoderm, suggesting that other repressors may be involved in its restriction.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Late in development, the same enhancer restricts expression to the tissues that will become the stomach and pancreas.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] An additional enhancer is responsible for maintaining *Gata4* expression in the endoderm during the intermediate stages of gut development.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Some genes involved in critical developmental processes contain multiple enhancers of overlapping function.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Secondary enhancers, or "shadow enhancers", may be found many kilobases away from the primary enhancer ("primary" usually refers to the first enhancer discovered, which is often closer to the gene it regulates).
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] On its own, each enhancer drives nearly identical patterns of gene expression.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Recent work has shown that multiple enhancers allow fruit flies to survive environmental perturbations, such as an increase in temperature.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] When raised at an elevated temperature, a single enhancer sometimes fails to drive the complete pattern of expression, whereas the presence of both enhancers permits normal gene expression.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] One theme of research in evolutionary developmental biology ("evo-devo") is investigating the role of enhancers and other cis-regulatory elements in producing morphological changes via developmental differences between species.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Recent work has investigated the role of enhancers in morphological changes in threespine stickleback fish.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Sticklebacks exist in both marine and freshwater environments, but sticklebacks in many freshwater populations have completely lost their pelvic fins (appendages homologous to the posterior limb of tetrapods).
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] *Pitx1* is a homeobox gene involved in posterior limb development in vertebrates.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Preliminary genetic analyses indicated that changes in the expression of this gene were responsible for pelvic reduction in sticklebacks.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Fish expressing only the freshwater allele of *Pitx1* do not have pelvic spines, whereas fish expressing a marine allele retain pelvic spines.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] A more thorough characterization showed that a 500 base pair enhancer sequence is responsible for turning on *Pitx1* expression in the posterior fin bud.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] This enhancer is located near a chromosomal fragile site—a sequence of DNA that is likely to be broken and thus more likely to be mutated as a result of imprecise DNA repair.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] This fragile site has caused repeated, independent losses of the enhancer responsible for driving *Pitx1* expression in the pelvic spines in isolated freshwater population, and without this enhancer, freshwater fish fail to develop pelvic spines.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Pigmentation patterns provide one of the most striking and easily scored differences between different species of animals.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Pigmentation of the *Drosophila* wing has proven to be a particularly amenable system for studying the development of complex pigmentation phenotypes.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] The *Drosophila guttifera* wing has 12 dark pigmentation spots and 4 lighter gray intervein patches.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Pigment spots arise from expression of the *yellow* gene, whose product produces black melanin.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Recent work has shown that two enhancers in the *yellow* gene produce gene expression in precisely this pattern – the vein spot enhancer drives reporter gene expression in the 12 spots, and the intervein shade enhancer drives reporter expression in the 4 distinct patches.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] These two enhancers are responsive to the Wnt signaling pathway, which is activated by *wingless* expression at all of the pigmented locations.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Thus, in the evolution of the complex pigmentation phenotype, the *yellow* pigment gene evolved enhancers responsive to the wingless signal and *wingless* expression evolved at new locations to produce novel wing patterns.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Each cell typically contains several hundred of a special class of enhancers that stretch over many kilobases long DNA sequences, called "super-enhancers".
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] These enhancers contain a large number of binding sites for sequence-specific, inducible transcription factors, and regulate expression of genes involved in cell differentiation.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] As a result, inflammation reprograms cells, altering their interactions with the rest of tissue and with the immune system.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] In cancer, proteins that control NF-κB activity are dysregulated, permitting malignant cells to decrease their dependence on interactions with local tissue, and hindering their surveillance by the immune system.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] In 1980, Max Birnstiel and Rudolf Grosschedl described an enhancer, which they referred to as a “modulator”.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] In 1981, an enhancer was described that originates from the polyomavirus SV40 and contains two identical 72 bp long sections called 72-bp repeats.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] It was shown that each of the two segments has a weak enhancing effect on the promoter on its own, but together they increase the activity many times over.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Synthetic regulatory elements such as enhancers promise to be a powerful tool to direct gene products to particular cell types in order to treat disease by activating beneficial genes or by halting aberrant cell states.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Since 2022, artificial intelligence and transfer learning strategies have led to a better understanding of the features of regulatory DNA sequences, the prediction, and the design of synthetic enhancers.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Building on work in cell culture, synthetic enhancers were successfully applied to entire living organisms in 2023.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] Using deep neural networks, scientists simulated the evolution of DNA sequences to analyze the emergence of features that underlie enhancer function.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] This allowed the design and production of a range of functioning synthetic enhancers for different cell types of the fruit fly brain.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] A second approach trained artificial intelligence models on single-cell DNA accessibility data and transferred the learned models towards the prediction of enhancers for selected tissues in the fruit fly embryo.
[src:chip-seq/enhancer-genetics] These enhancer prediction models were used to design synthetic enhancers for the nervous system, brain, muscle, epidermis and gut.
[src:chip-seq/histone] In biology, **histones** are highly-basic proteins abundant in lysine and arginine residues that are found in eukaryotic cell nuclei and in most Archaeal phyla.
[src:chip-seq/histone] They act as spools around which DNA winds to create structural units called nucleosomes.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Nucleosomes in turn are wrapped into 30-nanometer fibers that form tightly packed chromatin.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histones prevent DNA from becoming tangled and protect it from DNA damage.
[src:chip-seq/histone] In addition, histones play important roles in gene regulation and DNA replication.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Without histones, unwound DNA in chromosomes would be very long.
[src:chip-seq/histone] For example, each human cell has about 1.8 meters of DNA if completely stretched out; however, when wound about histones, this length is reduced to about 9 micrometers (0.009 mm) of 30 nm diameter chromatin fibers.
[src:chip-seq/histone] There are five families of histones, which are designated H1/H5 (linker histones), H2, H3, and H4 (core histones).
[src:chip-seq/histone] The nucleosome core is formed of two H2A-H2B dimers and a H3-H4 tetramer.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The tight wrapping of DNA around histones, is to a large degree, a result of electrostatic attraction between the positively charged histones and negatively charged phosphate backbone of DNA.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histones may be chemically modified through the action of enzymes to regulate gene transcription.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The most common modifications are the methylation of arginine or lysine residues or the acetylation of lysine.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Methylation can affect how other proteins such as transcription factors interact with the nucleosomes.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Lysine acetylation eliminates a positive charge on lysine thereby weakening the electrostatic attraction between histone and DNA, resulting in partial unwinding of the DNA, making it more accessible for gene expression.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Five major families of histone proteins exist: H1/H5, H2A, H2B, H3, and H4.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histones H2A, H2B, H3 and H4 are known as the core or nucleosomal histones, while histones H1/H5 are known as the **linker histones**.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The core histones all exist as dimers, which are similar in that they all possess the histone fold domain: three alpha helices linked by two loops.
[src:chip-seq/histone] It is this helical structure that allows for interaction between distinct dimers, particularly in a head-tail fashion (also called the handshake motif).
[src:chip-seq/histone] The resulting four distinct dimers then come together to form one octameric nucleosome core, approximately 63 Angstroms in diameter (a solenoid (DNA)-like particle).
[src:chip-seq/histone] Around 146 base pairs (bp) of DNA wrap around this core particle 1.65 times in a left-handed super-helical turn to give a particle of around 100 Angstroms across.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The linker histone H1 binds the nucleosome at the entry and exit sites of the DNA, thus locking the DNA into place and allowing the formation of higher order structure.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The most basic such formation is the 10 nm fiber or beads on a string conformation.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This involves the wrapping of DNA around nucleosomes with approximately 50 base pairs of DNA separating each pair of nucleosomes (also referred to as linker DNA).
[src:chip-seq/histone] Higher-order structures include the 30 nm fiber (forming an irregular zigzag) and 100 nm fiber, these being the structures found in normal cells.
[src:chip-seq/histone] During mitosis and meiosis, the condensed chromosomes are assembled through interactions between nucleosomes and other regulatory proteins.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histones are subdivided into canonical replication-dependent histones, whose genes are expressed during the S-phase of the cell cycle and replication-independent histone variants, expressed during the whole cell cycle.
[src:chip-seq/histone] In mammals, genes encoding canonical histones are typically clustered along chromosomes in 4 different highly-conserved loci, lack introns and use a stem loop structure at the 3' end instead of a polyA tail.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Genes encoding histone variants are usually not clustered, have introns and their mRNAs are regulated with polyA tails.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Complex multicellular organisms typically have a higher number of histone variants providing a variety of different functions.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Functionally, histone variants contribute to transcriptional control, epigenetic memory, and DNA repair, serving specialized functions beyond nucleosome packaging which plays distinct roles in chromatin dynamics.
[src:chip-seq/histone] For example, H2A.Z is enriched at regulatory elements and promoters of actively transcribed genes, where it modulates nucleosome stability and transcription factor binding.
[src:chip-seq/histone] In contrast, H3.3, a replacement variant of Histone H3, is associated with active transcription and is preferentially deposited at enhancer elements and transcribed gene bodies.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Another critical variant, CENPA, replaces H3 in centromeric nucleosomes, providing a structural foundation essential for chromosome segregation.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Variants also play essential roles in DNA repair.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Variants such as H2A.X are phosphorylated at sites of DNA damage, marking regions for recruitment of repair proteins.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This modification, commonly referred to as γH2A.X, serves as a key signal in the cellular response to double-strand breaks, facilitating efficient DNA repair processes.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Defects in histone variant regulation have been linked to genome instability, a hallmark of many cancers and age-related diseases.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Recent data are accumulating about the roles of diverse histone variants highlighting the functional links between variants and the delicate regulation of organism development.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histone variants proteins from different organisms, their classification and variant specific features can be found in "HistoneDB 2.0 - Variants" database.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Several pseudogenes have also been discovered and identified in very close sequences of their respective functional ortholog genes.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The nucleosome core is formed of two H2A-H2B dimers and a H3-H4 tetramer, forming two nearly symmetrical halves by tertiary structure (C2 symmetry; one macromolecule is the mirror image of the other).
[src:chip-seq/histone] The H2A-H2B dimers and H3-H4 tetramer also show pseudodyad symmetry.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The 4 'core' histones (H2A, H2B, H3 and H4) are relatively similar in structure and are highly conserved through evolution, all featuring a 'helix turn helix turn helix' motif (DNA-binding protein motif that recognize specific DNA sequence).
[src:chip-seq/histone] They also share the feature of long 'tails' on one end of the amino acid structure - this being the location of post-translational modification (see below).
[src:chip-seq/histone] Archaeal histone only contains a H3-H4 like dimeric structure made out of a single type of unit.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Such dimeric structures can stack into a tall superhelix ("hypernucleosome") onto which DNA coils in a manner similar to nucleosome spools.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Only some archaeal histones have tails; tails can also be replaced by a linker joining together two archael histone folds in a single protein chain, thereby giving place to a double histone fold protein.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The distance between the spools around which eukaryotic cells wind their DNA has been determined to range from 59 to 70 Å.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The highly basic nature of histones, aside from facilitating DNA-histone interactions, contributes to their water solubility.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histones are subject to post translational modification by enzymes primarily on their N-terminal tails, but also in their globular domains.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Such modifications include methylation, citrullination, acetylation, phosphorylation, SUMOylation, ubiquitination, and ADP-ribosylation.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This affects their function of gene regulation.
[src:chip-seq/histone] In general, genes that are active have less bound histone, while inactive genes are highly associated with histones during interphase.
[src:chip-seq/histone] It also appears that the structure of histones has been evolutionarily conserved, as any deleterious mutations would be severely maladaptive.
[src:chip-seq/histone] All histones have a highly positively charged N-terminus with many lysine and arginine residues.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Core histones are found in the nuclei of eukaryotic cells and in most Archaeal phyla, but not in bacteria.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The unicellular algae known as dinoflagellates were previously thought to be the only eukaryotes that completely lack histones, but later studies showed that their DNA still encodes histone genes.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Unlike the core histones, homologs of the lysine-rich linker histone (H1) proteins are found in bacteria, otherwise known as nucleoprotein HC1/HC2.
[src:chip-seq/histone] It has been proposed that core histone proteins are evolutionarily related to the helical part of the extended AAA+ ATPase domain, the C-domain, and to the N-terminal substrate recognition domain of Clp/Hsp100 proteins.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Despite the differences in their topology, these three folds share a homologous helix-strand-helix (HSH) motif.
[src:chip-seq/histone] It's also proposed that they may have evolved from ribosomal proteins (RPS6/RPS15), both being short and basic proteins.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Archaeal histones may well resemble the evolutionary precursors to eukaryotic histones.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histone proteins are among the most highly conserved proteins in eukaryotes, emphasizing their important role in the biology of the nucleus.
[src:chip-seq/histone] In contrast mature sperm cells largely use protamines to package their genomic DNA, most likely because this allows them to achieve an even higher packaging ratio.
[src:chip-seq/histone] There are some *variant* forms in some of the major classes.
[src:chip-seq/histone] They share amino acid sequence homology and core structural similarity to a specific class of major histones but also have their own feature that is distinct from the major histones.
[src:chip-seq/histone] These *minor histones* usually carry out specific functions of the chromatin metabolism.
[src:chip-seq/histone] For example, histone H3-like CENPA is associated with only the centromere region of the chromosome.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histone H2A variant H2A.Z is associated with the promoters of actively transcribed genes and also involved in the prevention of the spread of silent heterochromatin.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Furthermore, H2A.Z has roles in chromatin for genome stability.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Another H2A variant H2A.X is phosphorylated at S139 in regions around double-strand breaks and marks the region undergoing DNA repair.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histone H3.3 is associated with the body of actively transcribed genes.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histones act as spools around which DNA winds.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This enables the compaction necessary to fit the large genomes of eukaryotes inside cell nuclei: the compacted molecule is 40,000 times shorter than an unpacked molecule.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The effect of histones on transcription was established already in the late 1980s.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Specifically, when histones are mutated or depleted a substantial activation of transcription occurs and is independent of other transcription factors (or suggesting that the latter displace histones).
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histones undergo posttranslational modifications that alter their interaction with DNA and nuclear proteins.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The H3 and H4 histones have long tails protruding from the nucleosome, which can be covalently modified at several places.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Modifications of the tail include methylation, acetylation, phosphorylation, ubiquitination, SUMOylation, citrullination, and ADP-ribosylation.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The core of the histones H2A and H2B can also be modified.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Combinations of modifications, known as *histone marks*, are thought to constitute a code, the so-called "histone code".
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histone modifications act in diverse biological processes such as gene regulation, DNA repair, chromosome condensation (mitosis) and spermatogenesis (meiosis).
[src:chip-seq/histone] So H3K4me1 denotes the monomethylation of the 4th residue (a lysine) from the start (i.e., the N-terminal) of the H3 protein.
[src:chip-seq/histone] A huge catalogue of histone modifications have been described, but a functional understanding of most is still lacking.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Collectively, it is thought that histone modifications may underlie a histone code, whereby combinations of histone modifications have specific meanings.
[src:chip-seq/histone] However, most functional data concerns individual prominent histone modifications that are biochemically amenable to detailed study.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The addition of one, two, or many methyl groups to lysine has little effect on the chemistry of the histone; methylation leaves the charge of the lysine intact and adds a minimal number of atoms so steric interactions are mostly unaffected.
[src:chip-seq/histone] However, proteins containing Tudor, chromo or PHD domains, amongst others, can recognise lysine methylation with exquisite sensitivity and differentiate mono, di and tri-methyl lysine, to the extent that, for some lysines (e.g.: H4K20) mono, di and tri-methylation appear to have different meanings.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Because of this, lysine methylation tends to be a very informative mark and dominates the known histone modification functions.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Recently it has been shown, that the addition of a serotonin group to the position 5 glutamine of H3, happens in serotonergic cells such as neurons.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This is part of the differentiation of the serotonergic cells.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This post-translational modification happens in conjunction with the H3K4me3 modification.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The serotonylation potentiates the binding of the general transcription factor TFIID to the TATA box.
[src:chip-seq/histone] What was said above of the chemistry of lysine methylation also applies to arginine methylation, and some protein domains—e.g., Tudor domains—can be specific for methyl arginine instead of methyl lysine.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Arginine is known to be mono- or di-methylated, and methylation can be symmetric or asymmetric, potentially with different meanings.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Enzymes called peptidylarginine deiminases (PADs) hydrolyze the imine group of arginines and attach a keto group, so that there is one less positive charge on the amino acid residue.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This process has been involved in the activation of gene expression by making the modified histones less tightly bound to DNA and thus making the chromatin more accessible.
[src:chip-seq/histone] PADs can also produce the opposite effect by removing or inhibiting mono-methylation of arginine residues on histones and thus antagonizing the positive effect arginine methylation has on transcriptional activity.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Addition of an acetyl group has a major chemical effect on lysine as it neutralises the positive charge.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This reduces electrostatic attraction between the histone and the negatively charged DNA backbone, loosening the chromatin structure; highly acetylated histones form more accessible chromatin and tend to be associated with active transcription.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Lysine acetylation appears to be less precise in meaning than methylation, in that histone acetyltransferases tend to act on more than one lysine; presumably this reflects the need to alter multiple lysines to have a significant effect on chromatin structure.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Addition of a negatively charged phosphate group can lead to major changes in protein structure, leading to the well-characterised role of phosphorylation in controlling protein function.
[src:chip-seq/histone] It is not clear what structural implications histone phosphorylation has, but histone phosphorylation has clear functions as a post-translational modification, and binding domains such as BRCT have been characterised.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histone modifications are involved in control of transcription.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Despite the conservation of this complex and histone modification from yeast to mammals, it is not entirely clear what role this modification plays.
[src:chip-seq/histone] However, it is an excellent mark of active promoters and the level of this histone modification at a gene's promoter is broadly correlated with transcriptional activity of the gene.
[src:chip-seq/histone] which in turn adds a ubiquitin mark to H2B K123 (K120 in mammals).
[src:chip-seq/histone] H2BK123Ub occurs throughout transcribed regions, but this mark is required for COMPASS to trimethylate H3K4 at promoters.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This trimethylation occurs in the body of active genes and is deposited by the methyltransferase Set2.
[src:chip-seq/histone] , and H3K36Me3 is indicative of actively transcribed genes.
[src:chip-seq/histone] H3K36Me3 is recognised by the Rpd3 histone deacetylase complex, which removes acetyl modifications from surrounding histones, increasing chromatin compaction and repressing spurious transcription.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Increased chromatin compaction prevents transcription factors from accessing DNA, and reduces the likelihood of new transcription events being initiated within the body of the gene.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This process therefore helps ensure that transcription is not interrupted.
[src:chip-seq/histone] and is likely bound by other proteins to exert a repressive function.
[src:chip-seq/histone] and adds the histone modification H2AK119Ub which aids chromatin compaction.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Based on this data it appears that PRC1 is recruited through the action of PRC2, however, recent studies show that PRC1 is recruited to the same sites in the absence of PRC2.
[src:chip-seq/histone] , and is therefore strongly associated with gene repression.
[src:chip-seq/histone] although its functional importance remains unclear.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Analysis of histone modifications in embryonic stem cells (and other stem cells) revealed many gene promoters carrying both H3K4Me3 and H3K27Me3, in other words these promoters display both activating and repressing marks simultaneously.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This peculiar combination of modifications marks genes that are poised for transcription; they are not required in stem cells, but are rapidly required after differentiation into some lineages.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Once the cell starts to differentiate, these bivalent promoters are resolved to either active or repressive states depending on the chosen lineage.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Marking sites of DNA damage is an important function for histone modifications.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Without a repair marker, DNA would get destroyed by damage accumulated from sources such as the ultraviolet radiation of the sun.
[src:chip-seq/histone] H2AX is phosphorylated early after detection of DNA double strand break, and forms a domain extending many kilobases either side of the damage.
[src:chip-seq/histone] ) and as such, gamma H2AX forms a vital part of the machinery that ensures genome stability.
[src:chip-seq/histone] H3K56Acx is required for genome stability.
[src:chip-seq/histone] but is rapidly deacetylated around sites of DNA damage.
[src:chip-seq/histone] H3K56 acetylation is also required to stabilise stalled replication forks, preventing dangerous replication fork collapses.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Although in general mammals make far greater use of histone modifications than microorganisms, a major role of H3K56Ac in DNA replication exists only in fungi, and this has become a target for antibiotic development.
[src:chip-seq/histone] phosphorylates histone H3 at serine 10, triggering a cascade of changes that mediate mitotic chromosome condensation.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Condensed chromosomes therefore stain very strongly for this mark, but H3S10 phosphorylation is also present at certain chromosome sites outside mitosis, for example in pericentric heterochromatin of cells during G2.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Phosphorylation of H2B at serine 10 (yeast) or serine 14 (mammals) is also linked to chromatin condensation, but for the very different purpose of mediating chromosome condensation during apoptosis.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This mark is not simply a late acting bystander in apoptosis as yeast carrying mutations of this residue are resistant to hydrogen peroxide-induced apoptotic cell death.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Epigenetic modifications of histone tails in specific regions of the brain are of central importance in addictions.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Once particular epigenetic alterations occur, they appear to be long lasting "molecular scars" that may account for the persistence of addictions.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Cigarette smokers (about 15% of the US population) are usually addicted to nicotine.
[src:chip-seq/histone] After 7 days of nicotine treatment of mice, acetylation of both histone H3 and histone H4 was increased at the FosB promoter in the nucleus accumbens of the brain, causing 61% increase in FosB expression.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This would also increase expression of the splice variant Delta FosB.
[src:chip-seq/histone] In the nucleus accumbens of the brain, Delta FosB functions as a "sustained molecular switch" and "master control protein" in the development of an addiction.
[src:chip-seq/histone] About 7% of the US population is addicted to alcohol.
[src:chip-seq/histone] In rats exposed to alcohol for up to 5 days, there was an increase in histone 3 lysine 9 acetylation in the pronociceptin promoter in the brain amygdala complex.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This acetylation is an activating mark for pronociceptin.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The nociceptin/nociceptin opioid receptor system is involved in the reinforcing or conditioning effects of alcohol.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Methamphetamine addiction occurs in about 0.2% of the US population.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Chronic methamphetamine use causes methylation of the lysine in position 4 of histone 3 located at the promoters of the *c-fos* and the *C-C chemokine receptor 2 (ccr2)* genes, activating those genes in the nucleus accumbens (NAc). c-fos is well known to be important in addiction.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The *ccr2* gene is also important in addiction, since mutational inactivation of this gene impairs addiction.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histone chaperones are specialized proteins that assist in the proper handling, transport, and assembly of histones, preventing their aggregation and ensuring their appropriate deposition onto DNA.
[src:chip-seq/histone] These proteins play a crucial role in regulating nucleosome assembly and disassembly, influencing transcriptional activity, DNA replication, and repair.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Unlike enzymatic chromatin remodeling, histone chaperones function by binding histones in a regulated manner, modulating chromatin structure without direct catalytic activity.
[src:chip-seq/histone] One key function of histone chaperones is maintaining a reservoir of histones, regulating their supply to ensure proper chromatin formation.
[src:chip-seq/histone] During DNA replication and transcription, histone chaperones such as ASF1 and FACT facilitate nucleosome reassembly, ensuring the preservation of histone modifications that define cellular identity.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Moreover, histone chaperones contribute to nucleosome disassembly in response to cellular stress or DNA damage, thereby allowing access to repair machinery.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histone chaperones also participate in the selective deposition of histone variants, which are functionally distinct from canonical histones.
[src:chip-seq/histone] For example, HIRA is a chaperone that specifically deposits the histone variant H3.3, a marker of active chromatin regions.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Similarly, CAF-1 is responsible for incorporating H3.1 and H3.2 into newly replicated DNA, highlighting the functional specialization within chaperone networks.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Given their critical roles, misregulation of histone chaperones has been implicated in diseases such as cancer.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Aberrant chaperone activity can lead to improper histone deposition, genome instability, and altered gene expression, contributing to tumorigenesis.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Current research is exploring histone chaperones as potential therapeutic targets, particularly in cancers characterized by disrupted chromatin landscapes.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The coordinated action of multiple histone chaperones forms an intricate network responsible for histone transport, Chromatin assembly factor 1, and genome maintenance.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Chaperone networks facilitate the transport of histones which are synthesized in the cytoplasm and must be escorted to the cell nucleus.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This network ensures histones are deposited at the appropriate genomic locations, maintaining chromatin integrity and function.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histone chaperones play a crucial role in responding to DNA damage by regulating chromatin accessibility.
[src:chip-seq/histone] For example, in response to double strand breaks, chaperones such as FACT and ASF1 help disassemble nucleosomes at damage sites, allowing repair factors to access the lesion.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Once repair is completed, these chaperones facilitate the reassembly of nucleosomes, restoring chromatin structure and ensuring epigenetic information is maintained.
[src:chip-seq/histone] In addition to their role in genome stability, histone chaperones contribute to epigenetic inheritance.
[src:chip-seq/histone] During cell division, chromatin states must be faithfully propagated to daughter cells.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Chaperones help distribute parental histones onto newly synthesized DNA strands, preserving histone modifications and ensuring continuity of cellular identity.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Disruptions in these processes can lead to epigenetic abnormalities associated with developmental disorders.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The first step of chromatin structure duplication is the synthesis of histone proteins: H1, H2A, H2B, H3, H4.
[src:chip-seq/histone] These proteins are synthesized during S phase of the cell cycle.
[src:chip-seq/histone] There are different mechanisms which contribute to the increase of histone synthesis.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Yeast carry one or two copies of each histone gene, which are not clustered but rather scattered throughout chromosomes.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histone gene transcription is controlled by multiple gene regulatory proteins such as transcription factors which bind to histone promoter regions.
[src:chip-seq/histone] In budding yeast, the candidate gene for activation of histone gene expression is SBF.
[src:chip-seq/histone] SBF is a transcription factor that is activated in late G1 phase, when it dissociates from its repressor Whi5.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This occurs when Whi5 is phosphorylated by Cdc8 which is a G1/S Cdk.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Suppression of histone gene expression outside of S phases is dependent on Hir proteins which form inactive chromatin structure at the locus of histone genes, causing transcriptional activators to be blocked.
[src:chip-seq/histone] In metazoans the increase in the rate of histone synthesis is due to the increase in processing of pre-mRNA to its mature form as well as decrease in mRNA degradation; this results in an increase of active mRNA for translation of histone proteins.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The mechanism for mRNA activation has been found to be the removal of a segment of the 3' end of the mRNA strand, and is dependent on association with stem-loop binding protein (SLBP).
[src:chip-seq/histone] SLBP also stabilizes histone mRNAs during S phase by blocking degradation by the 3'hExo nuclease.
[src:chip-seq/histone] SLBP levels are controlled by cell-cycle proteins, causing SLBP to accumulate as cells enter S phase and degrade as cells leave S phase.
[src:chip-seq/histone] SLBP are marked for degradation by phosphorylation at two threonine residues by cyclin dependent kinases, possibly cyclin A/ cdk2, at the end of S phase.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Metazoans also have multiple copies of histone genes clustered on chromosomes which are localized in structures called Cajal bodies as determined by genome-wide chromosome conformation capture analysis (4C-Seq).
[src:chip-seq/histone] Nuclear protein ataxia-telangiectasia (NPAT), also known as nuclear protein coactivator of histone transcription, is a transcription factor which activates histone gene transcription on chromosomes 1 and 6 of human cells.
[src:chip-seq/histone] NPAT is also a substrate of cyclin E-Cdk2, which is required for the transition between G1 phase and S phase.
[src:chip-seq/histone] NPAT activates histone gene expression only after it has been phosphorylated by the G1/S-Cdk cyclin E-Cdk2 in early S phase.
[src:chip-seq/histone] This shows an important regulatory link between cell-cycle control and histone synthesis.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Histones were discovered in 1884 by Albrecht Kossel.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The word "histone" dates from the late 19th century and is derived from the German word *histon*, a word itself of uncertain origin, perhaps from Ancient Greek *ἵστημι* (hístēmi, "make stand") or *ἱστός* (histós, "loom").
[src:chip-seq/histone] In the early 1960s, before the types of histones were known and before histones were known to be highly conserved across taxonomically diverse organisms, James F.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Bonner and his collaborators began a study of these proteins that were known to be tightly associated with the DNA in the nucleus of higher organisms.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Bonner and his postdoctoral fellow Ru Chih C.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Huang showed that isolated chromatin would not support RNA transcription in the test tube, but if the histones were extracted from the chromatin, RNA could be transcribed from the remaining DNA.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Paul T'so and James Bonner had called together a World Congress on Histone Chemistry and Biology in 1964, in which it became clear that there was no consensus on the number of kinds of histone and that no one knew how they would compare when isolated from different organisms.
[src:chip-seq/histone] For example, they found Histone IV sequence to be highly conserved between peas and calf thymus.
[src:chip-seq/histone] However, their work on the biochemical characteristics of individual histones did not reveal how the histones interacted with each other or with DNA to which they were tightly bound.
[src:chip-seq/histone] During the 1980s, Yahli Lorch and Roger Kornberg showed that a nucleosome on a core promoter prevents the initiation of transcription in vitro, and Michael Grunstein demonstrated that histones repress transcription in vivo, leading to the idea of the nucleosome as a general gene repressor.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Relief from repression is believed to involve both histone modification and the action of chromatin-remodeling complexes.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Vincent Allfrey and Alfred Mirsky had earlier proposed a role of histone modification in transcriptional activation, regarded as a molecular manifestation of epigenetics.
[src:chip-seq/histone] Michael Grunstein and David Allis found support for this proposal, in the importance of histone acetylation for transcription in yeast and the activity of the transcriptional activator Gcn5 as a histone acetyltransferase.
[src:chip-seq/histone] The discovery of the H5 histone appears to date back to the 1970s, and it is now considered an isoform of Histone H1.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] In molecular biology, a **transcription factor** (**TF**) (or **sequence-specific DNA-binding factor**) is a protein that controls the rate of transcription of genetic information from DNA to messenger RNA, by binding to DNA sequences.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Specificity can be due to sequence motifs, or epigenetic modifications.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The function of TFs is to regulate—turn on and off—genes in order to make sure that they are expressed in the desired cells at the right time and in the right amount throughout the life of the cell and the organism.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Groups of TFs function in a coordinated fashion to direct cell division, cell growth, and cell death throughout life; cell migration and organization (body plan) during embryonic development; and intermittently in response to signals from outside the cell, such as a hormone.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] There are approximately 1600 TFs in the human genome, where half of them are C2H2 zinc fingers.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors are members of the proteome as well as regulome.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] TFs work alone or with other proteins in a complex, by promoting (as an activator), or blocking (as a repressor) the recruitment of RNA polymerase (the enzyme that performs the transcription of genetic information from DNA to RNA) to specific genes.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] A defining feature of TFs is that they contain at least one DNA-binding domain (DBD), which attaches to a specific sequence of DNA adjacent to the genes that they regulate.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] TFs are grouped into classes based on their DBDs.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Other proteins such as coactivators, chromatin remodelers, histone acetyltransferases, histone deacetylases, kinases, and methylases are also essential to gene regulation, but lack DNA-binding domains, and therefore are not TFs.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] TFs are of interest in medicine because TF mutations can cause specific diseases, and medications can be potentially targeted toward them.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors are essential for the regulation of gene expression and are, as a consequence, found in all living organisms.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The number of transcription factors found within an organism increases with genome size, and larger genomes tend to have more transcription factors per gene.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] There are approximately 2800 proteins in the human genome that contain DNA-binding domains, and 1600 of these are presumed to function as transcription factors, where half of them (~800) are C2H2 zinc finger proteins.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Therefore, approximately 10% of genes in the genome code for transcription factors, which makes this family the single largest family of human proteins.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Furthermore, genes are often flanked by several binding sites for distinct transcription factors, and efficient expression of each of these genes requires the cooperative action of several different transcription factors (see, for example, hepatocyte nuclear factors).
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Hence, the combinatorial use of a subset of the approximately 2000 human transcription factors easily accounts for the unique regulation of each gene in the human genome during development.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors bind to either enhancer or promoter regions of DNA adjacent to the genes that they regulate based on recognizing specific DNA motifs.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Depending on the transcription factor, the transcription of the adjacent gene is either up- or down-regulated.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors use a variety of mechanisms for the regulation of gene expression.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors are one of the groups of proteins that read and interpret the genetic "blueprint" in the DNA.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] They bind to the DNA and help initiate a program of increased or decreased gene transcription.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] As such, they are vital for many important cellular processes.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] In eukaryotes, an important class of transcription factors called general transcription factors (GTFs) are necessary for transcription to occur.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Many of these GTFs do not actually bind DNA, but rather are part of the large transcription preinitiation complex that interacts with RNA polymerase directly.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The most common GTFs are TFIIA, TFIIB, TFIID (see also TATA binding protein), TFIIE, TFIIF, and TFIIH.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The preinitiation complex binds to promoter regions of DNA upstream to the gene that they regulate.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Other transcription factors differentially regulate the expression of various genes by binding to enhancer regions of DNA adjacent to regulated genes.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] These transcription factors are critical to making sure that genes are expressed in the right cell at the right time and in the right amount, depending on the changing requirements of the organism.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Many transcription factors in multicellular organisms are involved in development.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Responding to stimuli, these transcription factors turn on/off the transcription of the appropriate genes, which, in turn, allows for changes in cell morphology or activities needed for cell fate determination and cellular differentiation.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The Hox transcription factor family, for example, is important for proper body pattern formation in organisms as diverse as fruit flies to humans.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Another example is the transcription factor encoded by the sex-determining region Y (SRY) gene, which plays a major role in determining sex in humans.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Cells can communicate with each other by releasing molecules that produce signaling cascades within another receptive cell.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] If the signal requires upregulation or downregulation of genes in the recipient cell, often transcription factors will be downstream in the signaling cascade.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The estrogen receptor then goes to the cell's nucleus and binds to its DNA-binding sites, changing the transcriptional regulation of the associated genes.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Not only do transcription factors act downstream of signaling cascades related to biological stimuli but they can also be downstream of signaling cascades involved in environmental stimuli.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Many transcription factors, especially some that are proto-oncogenes or tumor suppressors, help regulate the cell cycle and as such determine how large a cell will get and when it can divide into two daughter cells.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] One example is the Myc oncogene, which has important roles in cell growth and apoptosis.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors can also be used to alter gene expression in a host cell to promote pathogenesis.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] A well studied example of this are the transcription-activator like effectors (TAL effectors) secreted by Xanthomonas bacteria.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] When injected into plants, these proteins can enter the nucleus of the plant cell, bind plant promoter sequences, and activate transcription of plant genes that aid in bacterial infection.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] TAL effectors contain a central repeat region in which there is a simple relationship between the identity of two critical residues in sequential repeats and sequential DNA bases in the TAL effector's target site.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] This property likely makes it easier for these proteins to evolve in order to better compete with the defense mechanisms of the host cell.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] It is common in biology for important processes to have multiple layers of regulation and control.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] This is also true with transcription factors: Not only do transcription factors control the rates of transcription to regulate the amounts of gene products (RNA and protein) available to the cell but transcription factors themselves are regulated (often by other transcription factors).
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors (like all proteins) are transcribed from a gene on a chromosome into RNA, and then the RNA is translated into protein.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Any of these steps can be regulated to affect the production (and thus activity) of a transcription factor.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] An implication of this is that transcription factors can regulate themselves.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] For example, in a negative feedback loop, the transcription factor acts as its own repressor: If the transcription factor protein binds the DNA of its own gene, it down-regulates the production of more of itself.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] This is one mechanism to maintain low levels of a transcription factor in a cell.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] In eukaryotes, transcription factors (like most proteins) are transcribed in the nucleus but are then translated in the cell's cytoplasm.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Many proteins that are active in the nucleus contain nuclear localization signals that direct them to the nucleus.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] But, for many transcription factors, this is a key point in their regulation.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Important classes of transcription factors such as some nuclear receptors must first bind a ligand while in the cytoplasm before they can relocate to the nucleus.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors may be activated or deactivated through their signal-sensing or effector domains.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] However, not all transcription factors have an effector domain; for example, approximately 400 C2H2 zinc finger transcription factors contain only DNA-binding domains (DBDs).
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] In eukaryotes, DNA is organized with the help of histones into compact particles called nucleosomes, where sequences of about 147 DNA base pairs make ~1.65 turns around histone protein octamers.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] DNA within nucleosomes is inaccessible to many transcription factors.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Some transcription factors, so-called pioneer factors are still able to bind their DNA binding sites on the nucleosomal DNA.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] For most other transcription factors, the nucleosome should be actively unwound by molecular motors such as chromatin remodelers.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Alternatively, the nucleosome can be partially unwrapped by thermal fluctuations, allowing temporary access to the transcription factor binding site.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] In many cases, a transcription factor needs to compete for binding to its DNA binding site with other transcription factors and histones or non-histone chromatin proteins.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Pairs of transcription factors and other proteins can play antagonistic roles (activator versus repressor) in the regulation of the same gene.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Most transcription factors do not work alone.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Many large TF families form complex homotypic or heterotypic interactions through dimerization.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] For gene transcription to occur, a number of transcription factors must bind to DNA regulatory sequences.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] This collection of transcription factors, in turn, recruit intermediary proteins such as cofactors that allow efficient recruitment of the preinitiation complex and RNA polymerase.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Thus, for a single transcription factor to initiate transcription, all of these other proteins must also be present, and the transcription factor must be in a state where it can bind to them if necessary.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Cofactors are proteins that modulate the effects of transcription factors.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Cofactors are interchangeable between specific gene promoters; the protein complex that occupies the promoter DNA and the amino acid sequence of the cofactor determine its spatial conformation.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] For example, certain steroid receptors can exchange cofactors with NF-κB, which is a switch between inflammation and cellular differentiation; thereby steroids can affect the inflammatory response and function of certain tissues.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors and methylated cytosines in DNA both have major roles in regulating gene expression.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] (Methylation of cytosine in DNA primarily occurs where cytosine is followed by guanine in the 5' to 3' DNA sequence, a CpG site.) Methylation of CpG sites in a promoter region of a gene usually represses gene transcription, while methylation of CpGs in the body of a gene increases expression.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] TET enzymes play a central role in demethylation of methylated cytosines.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Demethylation of CpGs in a gene promoter by TET enzyme activity increases transcription of the gene.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The DNA binding sites of 519 transcription factors were evaluated.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Of these, 169 transcription factors (33%) did not have CpG dinucleotides in their binding sites, and 33 transcription factors (6%) could bind to a CpG-containing motif but did not display a preference for a binding site with either a methylated or unmethylated CpG.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] TET enzymes do not specifically bind to methylcytosine except when recruited (see DNA demethylation).
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] TET-mediated conversion of mC to hmC appears to disrupt the binding of 5mC-binding proteins including MECP2 and MBD (Methyl-CpG-binding domain) proteins, facilitating nucleosome remodeling and the binding of transcription factors, thereby activating transcription of those genes.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] EGR1 is an important transcription factor in memory formation.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] It has an essential role in brain neuron epigenetic reprogramming.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The transcription factor EGR1 recruits the TET1 protein that initiates a pathway of DNA demethylation.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] EGR1, together with TET1, is employed in programming the distribution of methylation sites on brain DNA during brain development and in learning (see Epigenetics in learning and memory).
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The portion (domain) of the transcription factor that binds DNA is called its DNA-binding domain.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The DNA sequence that a transcription factor binds to is called a transcription factor-binding site or response element.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors interact with their binding sites using a combination of electrostatic (of which hydrogen bonds are a special case) and Van der Waals forces.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Due to the nature of these chemical interactions, most transcription factors bind DNA in a sequence specific manner.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] However, not all bases in the transcription factor-binding site may actually interact with the transcription factor.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] In addition, some of these interactions may be weaker than others.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Thus, transcription factors do not bind just one sequence but are capable of binding a subset of closely related sequences, each with a different strength of interaction.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] For example, although the consensus binding site for the TATA-binding protein (TBP) is TATAAAA, the TBP transcription factor can also bind similar sequences such as TATATAT or TATATAA.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Because transcription factors can bind a set of related sequences and these sequences tend to be short, potential transcription factor binding sites can occur by chance if the DNA sequence is long enough.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] It is unlikely, however, that a transcription factor will bind all compatible sequences in the genome of the cell.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Other constraints, such as DNA accessibility in the cell or availability of cofactors may also help dictate where a transcription factor will actually bind.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Thus, given the genome sequence, it is still difficult to predict where a transcription factor will actually bind in a living cell.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Additional recognition specificity, however, may be obtained through the use of more than one DNA-binding domain (for example tandem DBDs in the same transcription factor or through dimerization of two transcription factors) that bind to two or more adjacent sequences of DNA.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors are of clinical significance for at least two reasons: (1) mutations can be associated with specific diseases, and (2) they can be targets of medications.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Due to their important roles in development, intercellular signaling, and cell cycle, some human diseases have been associated with mutations in transcription factors.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Many transcription factors are either tumor suppressors or oncogenes, and, thus, mutations or aberrant regulation of them is associated with cancer.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Three groups of transcription factors are known to be important in human cancer: (1) the NF-kappaB and AP-1 families, (2) the STAT family and (3) the steroid receptors.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Approximately 10% of currently prescribed drugs directly target the nuclear receptor class of transcription factors.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Examples include tamoxifen and bicalutamide for the treatment of breast and prostate cancer, respectively, and various types of anti-inflammatory and anabolic steroids.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] In addition, transcription factors are often indirectly modulated by drugs through signaling cascades.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] It might be possible to directly target other less-explored transcription factors such as NF-κB with drugs.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors outside the nuclear receptor family are thought to be more difficult to target with small molecule therapeutics since it is not clear that they are "drugable" but progress has been made on Pax2 and the notch pathway.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Gene duplications have played a crucial role in the evolution of species.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] This applies particularly to transcription factors.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Once they occur as duplicates, accumulated mutations encoding for one copy can take place without negatively affecting the regulation of downstream targets.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] However, changes of the DNA binding specificities of the single-copy Leafy transcription factor, which occurs in most land plants, have recently been elucidated.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] In that respect, a single-copy transcription factor can undergo a change of specificity through a promiscuous intermediate without losing function.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Similar mechanisms have been proposed in the context of all alternative phylogenetic hypotheses, and the role of transcription factors in the evolution of all species.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The transcription factors have a role in resistance activity which is important for successful biocontrol activity.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] There are different technologies available to analyze transcription factors.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] On the genomic level, DNA-sequencing and database research are commonly used.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The protein version of the transcription factor is detectable by using specific antibodies.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The sample is detected on a western blot.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] By using electrophoretic mobility shift assay (EMSA), the activation profile of transcription factors can be detected.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] A multiplex approach for activation profiling is a TF chip system where several different transcription factors can be detected in parallel.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The most commonly used method for identifying transcription factor binding sites is chromatin immunoprecipitation (ChIP).
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] This technique relies on chemical fixation of chromatin with formaldehyde, followed by co-precipitation of DNA and the transcription factor of interest using an antibody that specifically targets that protein.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The DNA sequences can then be identified by microarray or high-throughput sequencing (ChIP-seq) to determine transcription factor binding sites.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] If no antibody is available for the protein of interest, DamID may be a convenient alternative.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] As described in more detail below, transcription factors may be classified by their (1) mechanism of action, (2) regulatory function, or (3) sequence homology (and hence structural similarity) in their DNA-binding domains.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] They are also classified by 3D structure of their DBD and the way it contacts DNA.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Transcription factors are often classified based on the sequence similarity and hence the tertiary structure of their DNA-binding domains.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] The following classification is based on the 3D structure of their DBD and the way it contacts DNA.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] It was first developed for Human TF and later extended to rodents and also to plants.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] There are numerous databases cataloging information about transcription factors, but their scope and utility vary dramatically.
[src:chip-seq/transcription-factor] Some may contain only information about the actual proteins, some about their binding sites, or about their target genes.
